      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed at element sizes of 0.70 mm, 0.50 mm, and 0.35 mm (production mesh). Stiffness QoI changed by 3.1% between coarse and medium, and by 0.8% between medium and fine. GCI-based discretization uncertainty is 1.4% of the QoI at the production mesh density. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver convergence is confirmed by force residual norm below 1e-4 at each load step; energy balance checked.",
      "rationale": "All load steps converged within 25 iterations to a force residual norm below 1e-4. Energy balance error was below 0.05% across all 11 model instances. No solver warnings or non-convergence events were recorded in the output logs. Gradation 2 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup is reviewed by a second qualified analyst; a documented checklist covers boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions.",
      "rationale": "An independent peer review of the model setup was conducted by a second FEA engineer using the DePuy Synthes FEA review checklist (rev. 4.2). All 34 checklist items were verified. Boundary condition definitions, material property assignments, and contact pair formulations were confirmed consistent with the F1717 test fixture geometry. Gradation 2 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model selection is justified by material characterization data; contact formulation is appropriate for the expected slip regime.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V isotropic hardening parameters were derived from uniaxial tensile coupon data (n=6 coupons from the same material lot as the test constructs). The augmented Lagrangian contact formulation with a friction coefficient of 0.25 was validated against a standalone contact patch test. Geometric nonlinearity is enabled to capture large-rotation kinematics at 40 mm displacement. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric dimensions are traceable to measured values; uncertainty in inputs is quantified and propagated.",
      "rationale": "Screw and rod dimensions were measured by CMM on three production parts per component; mean dimensions used in the nominal model. Material elastic modulus and yield stress distributions were characterized from coupon testing; a one-at-a-time sensitivity study confirmed that yield stress is the dominant input uncertainty contributor (sensitivity index 0.61). Input uncertainty contribution to QoI uncertainty is 3.8%, within the 5% budget. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test specimens are production-representative; sample size supports statistical comparison; traceability to manufacturing lot is documented.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-representative components (same material lot and manufacturing process as commercial product). Specimens were distributed across two independent test laboratories (n=6 Lab A, n=5 Lab B) to assess inter-laboratory variability. Lot traceability certificates are on file. Statistical power analysis confirmed 80% power to detect a 5% QoI difference at alpha=0.05 with N=11. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of loading scenarios relevant to the COU, including at minimum two distinct load configurations.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 load configuration (static compression-bending at a fixed offset). Although the protocol is standardized and directly relevant to the COU, only one loading condition was evaluated. Fatigue and torsion loading were outside the scope of this COU. Gradation 2 is achieved, which is below the required Gradation 3; this gap is accepted by the credibility assessment team on the basis that the COU is explicitly scoped to static compression-bending only.",
      "belowRequiredLevel": true
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) are demonstrably equivalent to the test article parameters used in the validation experiments.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table maps each model input to its experimental counterpart, with measured values from both the test specimens and the CMM survey of the production components. Maximum geometric deviation between nominal model and measured specimens is 0.04 mm, within the 0.1 mm equivalency tolerance. Material property equivalency is confirmed by coupon testing from the same lot. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E/uval) is pre-specified; comparison is performed for all primary QoIs; results are presented with uncertainty bands.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs were pre-specified in the V&V plan: construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. The E/uval metric was selected per ASME V&V 40 Section 8. Validation uncertainty uval incorporates numerical uncertainty (1.4%), input uncertainty (3.8%), and experimental measurement uncertainty (2.1%), combined by RSS. All three E/uval values (0.43, 0.61, 0.29) are below the 1.96 threshold. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in validation are directly linked to the failure modes and performance metrics identified in the risk analysis for the COU.",
      "rationale": "The device risk analysis identifies screw-rod construct stiffness and yield force as primary structural performance metrics governing clinical outcome under compressive-bending loading. Force at 40 mm displacement is a regulatory benchmark per ASTM F1717. All three QoIs are therefore directly relevant to the COU. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation scenario (geometry, loading, boundary conditions, material) is sufficiently similar to the COU scenario that the validation evidence supports the credibility claim.",
      "rationale": "The validation scenario replicates the COU scenario in all material respects: same screw diameter (7.5 mm), same non-cannulated geometry, same UHMWPE block surrogate, same F1717 fixture kinematics, same static loading mode. The validation constructs were assembled from the same production component lot as the commercial product. The only departure from the clinical scenario is the use of a standardized block surrogate in place of cadaveric bone, which is consistent with the regulatory precedent for this device class. Gradation 3 is achieved."
    }
